2 download_data function

  • Load the target data from Zillow Research.
  • Possible choices are State, Metro, County, City, Zip.
    • The default choice is Metro.
download_data = function(file_name = "Metro") {
  downloaded_file = read.csv(file = paste("http://files.zillowstatic.com/research/public/",file_name,"/",file_name,"_Zhvi_AllHomes.csv", sep=""), header = TRUE)
}

3 split_data function

  • Split the dataset to meta_data and data. Remove the rows with NA.
  • The output of the function is a list, which consists of two parts: meta_data and data.
    • meta_data contains the descriptive data of each row.
    • data contains the actual HPI values.
split_data = function(downloaded_file) {
  #extract the column names
  column_name = colnames(downloaded_file)
  
  #extract the first character from each column name to check which does not equal to "X", the result would be the column index number of "meta data"
  meta_data_scope = which(substr(column_name, start=1, stop=1) != "X")
  meta_data = downloaded_file[,meta_data_scope]
  
  #the column index number of "data" would be the rest
  data_scope = (length(meta_data)+1):length(downloaded_file)
  data = downloaded_file[,data_scope]
  
  #find the rows that start with NA, and remove those rows from "meta data" and "data"
  na_rows = which(is.na(data[,1])==TRUE)
  meta_data = meta_data[-c(na_rows),]
  data = data[-c(na_rows),]
  splitted_file = list(meta_data, data)
}

4 convert_data_type function

  • Convert the data type from “factor” to “character” after splitting the file. Only meta_data has “factor” column(s).
convert_data_type = function(splitted_file) {
  data = splitted_file[[2]]
  meta_data = splitted_file[[1]]
  meta_data_length = length(meta_data)
  for (i in 1:meta_data_length) {
    if (class(meta_data[,i]) == "factor") {
      meta_data[,i] = as.character(meta_data[,i])
    }
  }
  converted_data = list("meta_data" = meta_data, "data" = data)
}

5 possible_RegionName function

  • Give user all the Region Names that could be used for analysis.
possible_RegionName = function(converted_file) {
  meta_data = converted_file[[1]]
  RegionName_position = which(colnames(meta_data) == "RegionName")
  possible_names = meta_data[,RegionName_position]
}

6 logarithmization function

  • Convert the HPI values to HPI log return values.

\[r_t=\ln\left(\frac{\text{HPI}_t}{\text{HPI}_{t-1}}\right)\]

logarithmization = function(input_data) {
  log_data = log(input_data[2:length(input_data)]/input_data[1:(length(input_data)-1)])
}

7 HPI_plot function and log_HPI_plot function

HPI_plot = function(data) {
  main_title = paste("HPI values of ", input_RegionName, sep="")
  plot(data, type = "l", main = main_title, ylab = "HPI Values", xlab = "Time")
}
log_HPI_plot = function(data) {
  main_title = paste("Log Return of ", input_RegionName, sep="")
  plot(data, type = "l", main = main_title, ylab = "Log Return Values", xlab = "Time")
}

8 log_return_arima_model_selection function

  • Input a series of log return values.
  • The output of the function is a list, which consists of two parts: order and fixed.
    • order is the selected order of the ARIMA model.
    • fixed is the selected fixed parameter for the internal ARMA determination.
log_return_arima_model_selection = function(input_log_return) {
  diff = input_log_return %>% diff()
  armasubset_summary = armasubsets(diff, nar = 10, nma = 10) %>% summary()
  
  ### Select the BIC part from the ARMA subset summary
  BIC_values = armasubset_summary[["BIC"]]
  
  ### Get the row index number with the smallest BIC value
  BIC_min_position = which(BIC_values == BIC_values %>% min())
  
  ### Get the AR part and MA part seperately
  ar_part = armasubset_summary[["which"]][BIC_min_position, 2:11] %>% unname()
  ma_part = armasubset_summary[["which"]][BIC_min_position, 12:21] %>% unname()
  #ar_part; ma_part
  
  ### Get the shaded squares' positions of both AR part and MA part, and combine them as the shaded squares' positions of ARMA model
  ar_position = which(ar_part == TRUE)
  ma_position = which(ma_part == TRUE)
  #ar_position; ma_position
  if (length(ar_position) != 0) {
    positions = c(ar_position, max(ar_position) + ma_position)
  }
  if (length(ar_position) == 0) {
    positions = ma_position
  }
  #positions
  
  ### Use the shaded squares' positions of the ARMA model to form the value string of the fixed ARMA parameter
  fixed_parameter = rep(0, times = max(positions))
  fixed_parameter[positions] = NA
  #fixed_parameter
  
  ### Use the arima() from "stats" to create the best model based on the previous work
  #best_model = stats::arima(input_log_return, order=c(max(ar_position),1,max(ma_position)), fixed=fixed_parameter)
  if (length(ar_position) == 0 & length(ma_position) != 0) {
    output_order = c(0, 1, max(ma_position))
  }
  if (length(ar_position) != 0 & length(ma_position) == 0) {
    output_order = c(max(ar_position), 1, 0)
  }
  if (length(ar_position) != 0 & length(ma_position) != 0) {
    output_order = c(max(ar_position), 1, max(ma_position))
  }
  output_fixed = fixed_parameter
  output = list("order" = output_order, "fixed" = output_fixed)
}

10 Test

  • The first 3 columns of State are RegionID, RegionName, SizeRank.
  • The first 3 columns of Metro are RegionID, RegionName, SizeRank.
  • The first 7 columns of County are RegionID, RegionName, State, Metro, StateCodeFIPS, MunicipalCodeFIPS, SizeRank.
  • The first 6 columns of City are RegionID, RegionName, State, Metro, CountyName, SizeRank.
  • The first 7 columns of Zip are RegionID, RegionName, City, State, Metro, CountyName, SizeRank.

10.1 United States

input_RegionName = Metro_names[1]

current_RegionName_data = Metro[[2]][input_RegionName,] %>% as.numeric() %>% ts(frequency = 12, start = c(1996, 4))
current_RegionName_log_data = current_RegionName_data %>% logarithmization()

current_RegionName_data %>% HPI_plot()

current_RegionName_log_data %>% log_HPI_plot()

model_par = current_RegionName_log_data %>% log_return_arima_model_selection()
fc_mdl = stats::arima(current_RegionName_log_data,order=model_par[[1]],fixed=model_par[[2]])
ts_fc = forecast(fc_mdl,h=24,level=c(50,75,95))
plot(ts_fc,shadecols=c("gray","orange","red"))
